{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01LKN8EvJYLiJVMVaDsBS8cC","type":"tool_result","content":"28-\n29-The workflow engine gains a **hierarchical flow model** with three levels. Sprint-level flow schedules epics (potentially in parallel). Epic-level flow schedules stories and runs an epic retro on completion. Story-level flow is the existing `implement → verify → loop` pipeline. Each level has distinct lifecycle hooks: per-story telemetry (zero-token, engine-handled) and per-epic retrospectives (LLM-powered, one call per epic instead of per-session).\n30-\n31:Parallel execution requires **isolation**. Each parallel dispatch gets its own git worktree — a separate working directory on a separate branch. Stories within a worktree execute sequentially. When an epic completes, its worktree branch merges back to main. If merge conflicts occur, a merge agent resolves them with context from both branches.\n32-\n33-Three additional optimizations ship with this: **`agent: null` tasks** let the engine handle telemetry without LLM dispatch (saving ~$120-180/sprint on retro overhead), **verify flag propagation** moves flag-setting from the evaluator to the engine (fixing unreliable verification), and **coverage deduplication** eliminates redundant coverage runs during verification.\n34-\n35-### What Makes This Special\n36-\n37:- **Worktree-isolated parallelism** — each parallel epic runs in its own git worktree. No shared mutable state during execution. Conflicts surface only at merge time, handled by a merge agent.\n38-- **Hierarchical flow model** — sprint → epic → story, each with its own lifecycle. Not a flat task queue — a structured execution DAG with dependency-aware scheduling.\n39-- **Zero-token engine tasks** — `agent: null` tasks execute without LLM dispatch. Telemetry collection, flag setting, and state bookkeeping become free operations.\n40-- **Multi-lane TUI** — parallel execution visualized as concurrent workflow lanes, each showing its own story progress, driver, and cost.\n--\n44-\n45-- **Project Type:** Developer tool — npm CLI extending existing workflow engine\n46-- **Domain:** General software development tooling\n47:- **Complexity:** High — git worktree lifecycle, multi-process orchestration, merge conflict resolution, hierarchical state machines, multi-lane TUI rendering\n48-- **Project Context:** Brownfield — workflow engine, driver layer, TUI, state management all exist. This adds parallelism, hierarchy, and merge on top.\n49-\n50-## Success Criteria\n--\n52-### User Success\n53-\n54-- **Sprint time reduction:** 2x parallel execution delivers ~2x wall-clock speedup. Target: 19-story sprint in <4h (vs current 8h+).\n55:- **Zero merge failures:** Worktree isolation prevents file conflicts during execution. Merge agent resolves conflicts automatically. Target: <5% require manual intervention.\n56-- **Retro cost elimination:** Per-session LLM retros replaced by zero-token telemetry. Target: $0 token cost for per-story data collection.\n57-- **Parallel visibility:** User sees all active lanes in TUI — which epics running, which stories active, cost per lane.\n58-\n59-### Business Success\n60-\n61:- **3-month goal:** Parallel epic execution with worktrees, merge agent, and cross-worktree test validation working end-to-end. 2x speedup demonstrated.\n62-- **6-month goal:** Parallel stories within epics. DAG-based scheduling. Configurable parallelism at 3-4 lanes.\n63-- **Cost reduction:** ~$120-180/sprint from retro optimization. Additional savings from reduced wall-clock time.\n64-\n--\n92-- `scope: per-epic` — epic-level lifecycle hooks (retro)\n93-- Parallel epic execution with git worktree isolation (configurable, default 2)\n94-- Worktree lifecycle — create branch, create worktree, execute, merge, cleanup\n95:- Merge agent — LLM-powered automatic conflict resolution\n96-- Cross-worktree test validation — full test suite on merged result before accepting\n97-- Engine verify flag propagation — engine sets flags from output contract\n98-- Coverage deduplication — dev phase only, verify reads from contract\n--\n139-\n140-**Climax:** Epic 14 finishes first (3 stories vs 5). The engine runs the per-epic telemetry summary, then triggers the epic-14 retro task (analyst agent reads telemetry, produces findings). Then it merges the `epic-14-tui-workflow` branch back to main. The cross-worktree test suite runs on the merged result — all tests pass. The worktree is cleaned up. Lane 2 picks up epic-11 (next independent epic).\n141-\n142:**Resolution:** The sprint completes in 4.5 hours instead of 8+. BMad glances at the TUI — 6 epics done, 2 merge conflicts auto-resolved by the merge agent, 0 manual interventions, total cost $245 (vs $271 sequential due to fewer rate-limit waits).\n143-\n144----\n145-\n146-### Journey 2: The Engine — Handling a Merge Conflict\n147-\n148:Epic 10 (driver interface) and epic 11 (workflow schema) both modified `workflow-engine.ts`. Epic 10 finishes and merges cleanly. Epic 11 finishes, and the merge hits a conflict.\n149-\n150:**Opening:** The engine detects the conflict after `git merge` returns non-zero. It reads the conflict markers from `workflow-engine.ts`.\n151-\n152:**Rising Action:** The engine dispatches a merge agent (dev agent with merge context):\n153-```\n154-Merge conflict in src/lib/workflow-engine.ts\n155-\n--\n159-Both changes are in different functions — no semantic conflict, only git hunk overlap.\n160-```\n161-\n162:**Climax:** The merge agent resolves the conflict — both changes are additive, different functions, no semantic overlap. It commits the resolution. The cross-worktree test suite runs — all tests pass.\n163-\n164-**Resolution:** The merge completes automatically. The TUI shows: `[MERGE] epic-11 → main: auto-resolved (1 file)`. BMad never opened a terminal.\n165-\n--\n218-\n219-**4. Merge Agent Pattern**\n220-\n221:LLM-powered merge conflict resolution with full semantic context from both branches. Not a text-level merge — the agent understands what both epics were building and resolves accordingly.\n222-\n223-## Developer Tool Specific Requirements\n224-\n--\n292-### Merge & Validation\n293-\n294-- FR12: System can merge an epic's branch into main after epic completion\n295:- FR13: System can detect merge conflicts from failed `git merge`\n296:- FR14: System can dispatch a merge agent with conflict context from both branches\n297-- FR15: System can run the full test suite on the merged result before accepting\n298:- FR16: System can reject a merge and escalate to the user if tests fail after conflict resolution\n299-- FR17: User can configure merge strategy (rebase or merge-commit)\n300-\n301-### Engine-Handled Tasks\n--\n320-\n321-- FR27: System can render multiple concurrent workflow graphs (one per active lane) in the Ink TUI\n322-- FR28: System can display a summary bar showing active lanes, total cost, and merge status\n323:- FR29: System can show merge progress and conflict resolution status in the TUI\n324-- FR30: System can render lane completion (worktree merged, tests passed) as a distinct visual state\n325-\n326-### Out of Scope (Explicitly Excluded from MVP)\n--\n351-\n352-- NFR11: Git worktree commands must work with the project's existing git hooks\n353-- NFR12: Worktree branches must not conflict with user's existing branches (prefix with `codeharness/`)\n354:- NFR13: Telemetry NDJSON format must be stable across versions (versioned entries)"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_01WnnpXgRY1Zao1mENPUGorH","session_id":"74f4684f-cc80-4828-8405-943cba326449","uuid":"6fc0b1e1-cec3-40cf-b825-3565e018ab93","timestamp":"2026-04-03T21:41:49.049Z"}
